volved in invasion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with pneumonia and epiglottitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be the causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Escherichia coli","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Haemophilus influenzae","Pseudomonas aeruginosa"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a fastidious gram-negative coccobacillus that requires specific growth factors (X and V factors) for laboratory culture. It possesses several virulence factors including IgA protease which breaks down secretory IgA, endotoxin, and a polysaccharide capsule. These characteristics, along with its outer membrane proteins, enable tissue invasion leading to serious infections like pneumonia and epiglottitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-negative rod that is not fastidious and does not typically cause epiglottitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-positive diplococcus, not a gram-negative organism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-fastidious encapsulated gram-negative rod that rarely causes epiglottitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-fastidious gram-negative rod that does not typically cause epiglottitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Haemophilus influenzae is a gram-negative coccobacillus with IgA protease, endotoxin, and a polysaccharide capsule that can cause invasive disease.","Classic presentations of invasive Haemophilus influenzae include pneumonia and epiglottitis.","Fastidious organisms have complex nutritional requirements for growth in laboratory conditions.","Key virulence factors of Haemophilus influenzae include IgA protease, endotoxin, and outer membrane proteins."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Khattak ZE, Anjum F. Haemophilus influenzae Infection. [Updated 2023 Apr 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562176/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51887"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14945"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51887"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T09:12:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T09:14:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7633"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66436"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}